04967nam a22008055i 9781782043430DE-B159720240306010644.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20142014xxk    fo  d z      eng d  a97817820434307 a10.1515/97817820434302doi  a(DE-B1597)674939  a(OCoLC)1420507221  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxkcUK 4aPT143.O75bP73 2023 7aLIT0041702bisacsh04a830.9/3585qOCoLC223/eng/202311201 aPrager, Debra N., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aOrienting the Self :bThe German Literary Encounter with the Eastern Other /cDebra N. Prager.31aWoodbridge, Suffolk : bBoydell and Brewer, c[2014] 1bCamden House, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (344 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies in German Literature Linguistics and Culture ;v15400tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1: The Vision of the Eastern Other in Wolfram von Eschenbach’s Parzival -- t2: Mapping the World and the Self: Fortunatus and the Age of Discovery -- t3: Discovering the “Great Orient within Us”: Novalis’s Heinrich von Ofterdingen -- t4: The Oedipal and the Orient in Theodor Fontane’s Effi Briest -- t5: “The Asian Principle” in Thomas Mann’s Der Zauberberg -- tConclusion -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFollows the evolution of the Orient as a positive literary device in German literature and demonstrates how it was used to explore subjectivity and the possibility of wholeness.For centuries, Europe's eastward gaze has been wary if not hostile. Medieval man envisaged grotesque beings at the world's edge and scanned the steppes and straits on the immediate horizon for the Asian or Arab hordes that might swarm across them. Through the Crusades, the early modern era, and the age of imperialism, Europeans regarded the Eastern subject as requiring both "discovery" and conquest. Conveniently, the "Oriental" came to represent fanaticism, terrorism, moral laxity, and inscrutability, among other stereotypes. The list of German literary works that reinforced negative clichés about the East is long, but Orienting the Self argues for the presence in the Germanliterary tradition of a powerful perception of the East as the scene of desire, fantasy, and fulfillment. It follows the evolution of the Orient as a literary device and demonstrates how it was used to explore subjectivity and the possibility of wholeness. The five works treated in this study - Parzival, Fortunatus, Effi Briest, Heinrich von Ofterdingen, and The Magic Mountain - are narratives of development in which the encounter with the East is central to the progression toward selfhood and the promise of fulfillment. Debra N. Prager is Associate Professor of German at Washington and Lee University.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aGerman literaturexAsian influences. 0aGerman literaturexHistory and criticism. 0aOrientalism in literature. 0aOutsiders in literature. 0aSelf in literature. 0aSubjectivity in literature. 4aEnglish & American Literature. 4aGerman Literature. 4aMedieval Literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / German.2bisacsh  aDebra N. Prager.  aEastern subject.  aEffi Briest.  aEurope's eastward gaze.  aFortunatus.  aGerman literary tradition.  aGerman literature.  aHeinrich von Ofterdingen.  aOrient.  aOriental.  aParzival.  aThe Magic Mountain.  aWashington and Lee University.  aliterary device.  asubjectivity.  awholeness.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2014z978311143136940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781782043430?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781782043430423Coveruhttps